{
  "doc_id": "14248",
  "text": "One approach to block the acute and adaptive effects of drug exposure, therefore, is to interfere with glutamatergic neurotransmission. Levetiracetam (LEV) (S-a-ethyl-2-oxopyrrolidine acetamide) is an antiepileptic drug that decreases excitatory transmission preferentially at more active synapses in vitro [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . LEV selectively binds to synaptic vesicle glycoprotein 2A (SV2A) in presynaptic terminals throughout the brain [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . SV2A interacts with the calcium-sensor synaptotagmin through its N-terminal (cytosolic) domain [CITATION_6] and appears to have a modulatory rather than a necessary role in vesicular neurotransmitter release, as SV2A knockout mice show reduction but not elimination of excitatory neurotransmission [CITATION_7] .",
